pullRequest.body:
Add a more general version of the Jacobi theta function with a second variable, and prove the transformation law for this more general function rather than just for the one-variable version. Preparatory to functional equations for Dirichlet L-functions.

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion rw [← mul_neg, mul_assoc, mul_assoc, mul_le_mul_left two_pos, mul_comm, neg_mul, ← mul_neg] ```
Maybe we should add `I^4=1`, since we will inevitably need it in the future.
OK, I moved this to `Data.Complex.Basic`, but now I need to wait for almost the whole of mathlib to recompile! Time  for a lunch break 🥪 🍏 🫖
If you state it with `T ^ (2 : ℤ)` (and in the suffices) the  you can get rid of the `have`, although I haven't tested if itll break somewhere else...

Unlikely. because nothing quotes this lemma yet. (I wanted to prepare the ground for proving that even powers of $\theta$ are modular forms; but that relies on the algebraic fact that the group generated by $T^2$ and $S$ contains $\Gamma(2)$, and mathlib doesn't know this, AFAIK.)
Anyway this lemma is copied verbatim from the existing code so I'd rather leave it as it is for now.
Ah I see, then yeah maybe leave it for now then.
Do you think this is worth being it own lemma? I can imagine it being used again in the future.
Moved to `Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Exp`
There is an extra space after the `+`.Sorry,  I don't know how to do the comments that you can just click to add the changes.

> Sorry, I don't know how to do the comments that you can just click to add the changes.

That's the first icon in the header above the comment box (looks like a sheet of paper with $\pm$ on it). It's most useful if you select a block of code at a time to comment on, rather than just one line, by dragging over the "+" signs at the start of the lines in the "Files changed" view.
Ah thank you!

```suggestion
  ∑' n : ℤ, cexp (2 * π * I * ↑n * z + π * I * n ^ 2 * τ)
```
Maybe generalize this to `exp (-n * x)` with positive `x`? I'd expect this to be more useful than the special case `x = 1`.
Good point, I added a lemma showing that `Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ exp (n * a)) ↔ a < 0` and deduced the case at hand from this.

```suggestion
  rw [integral_add_right_eq_self fun a : ℝ ↦ cexp (- -b * (↑a + ↑(c / (2 * b)).im * I) ^ 2),
```
Why does the one-variable file import the two-variable file? This seems counter-intuitive.

OK, I see that some material from that file seems to be used further down.
Maybe one can collect what is needed for both in a "Basic" file and import that from both? But I haven't looked carefully at what needs what, so this may not be reasonable...
I take it back :smile: I had to realize that the one-variable function is a special case of the two-variable function...

```suggestion
    jacobiTheta₂ z τ =
      1 / (-I * τ) ^ (1 / 2 : ℂ) * cexp (-π * I * z ^ 2 / τ) * jacobiTheta₂ (z / τ) (-1 / τ) := by
```
I think this reads better.

```suggestion
`θ z τ = ∑' (n : ℤ), cexp (2 * π * I * n * z + π * I * n ^ 2 * τ)`.
```

```suggestion
theorem I_pow_four : I ^ 4 = 1 := by rw [(by norm_num : 4 = 2 * 2), pow_mul, I_sq, neg_one_sq]
```
I suspect this is the usual spelling.
The fact that the `↑` is needed makes me thinking we are missing something, but we can add it in another PR.
Indeed, this particular lemma is not changed in the present PR (just moved around)
